So overall - if you’re willing to spend the extra money - I’d recommend the Logitech Rally every time. It’s about as good of a PC-based conf room system as you can buy (hopefully they integrate the software live speaker switching sometime soon).

But in the 2 most important areas - mic quality and camera quality - the Logitech Rally absolutely crushes the Poly Studio. The Poly Studio has a bit of a ‘large room’ audio sound (that I hate) and the camera image was a bit pixelated when zoomed into the far end of the table.
On the speaker output quality - both were roughly the same (not that you’re playing music out of the speaker often).

Poly definitely wins the ‘sexiness’ category as well as the software-based auto zooming to current speaker (that works really great and I suspect will become a standard feature of all conf cams). Also comes with all mounting brackets vs having to pay $150 for Rally brackets.

Poly Studio was $800 and Rally was $2k. Rally comes with separate speaker and mic extension while Studio is all-in-one. Logitech also comes with a ‘table hub’ (which adds ability to hard wire laptops into it - but adds unnecessary complexity and likely never used).

How fucked up are our priorities that we've emulated the technologies of our science fiction, but refused to learn the lessons imparted about our humanity?

At some point, I entered the future and so much of it looks and sounds like the past that I didn't notice. I still don't have a flying car or a jetpack or public slideways or teleporters or pneumatic transit. Yet. And the social unrest of my parents' time is still unresolved.

I pull another small computer out of my pocket - it is in communication with the one on my wrist and with that same global network. I begin describing this simple interaction, purchasing a soda, using the language of the fiction I grew up with.

All of this happens through a network of computers spanning the globe, coupled with short-range radio communication. It strikes me that all of these things would have been pure fantasy not long ago. Feasible, sure, but for some far-off future date.

Once that connection is made, wirelessly, between two computers, and a third computer elsewhere, the screen in front of me lets me know that it is ready. I press a glowing button on the vending machine. The screen alerts me to a charge made to my account.

With a touch, the face of my watch stops displaying the time. A few more touches, and a small image of my debit card appears. I hold it up to a small computer screen. There's a slight vibration to let me know a connection is made.
